RIGHT JOIN in SQL

RIGHT JOIN (or RIGHT OUTER JOIN) is used to retrieve all records from the right table and the matching records from the left table based on a common column.

If there is no match in the left table, NULL values are returned for the left table's columns.

Syntax

SELECT column1, column2, ...
FROM table1
RIGHT JOIN table2
ON table1.common_column = table2.common_column;

Example

Employee Table

| emp_id | emp_name | dept_id |
| ------ | -------- | ------- |
| 1      | Hitesh   | 101     |
| 2      | Rahul    | 102     |
| 3      | Amit     | 103     |
| 4      | Neha     | 105     |

Department Table

| dept_id | dept_name |
| ------- | --------- |
| 101     | IT        |
| 102     | HR        |
| 103     | Finance   |
| 104     | Sales     |

Query

SELECT
    e.emp_id,
    e.emp_name,
    d.dept_name
FROM Employee e
RIGHT JOIN Department d
ON e.dept_id = d.dept_id;


Output

| emp_id | emp_name | dept_name |
| ------ | -------- | --------- |
| 1      | Hitesh   | IT        |
| 2      | Rahul    | HR        |
| 3      | Amit     | Finance   |
| NULL   | NULL     | Sales     |

Explanation:

- All records from the Department table are returned.
- Matching employee details are fetched from the Employee table.
- Since Sales (dept_id = 104) has no matching employee, NULL is returned for emp_id and emp_name.
